   <p>It's a writer's fantasy. You author a book. It hits the young adult jackpot. It sells 10 million copies. Hollywood actors fight for parts in the movie.</p>   <p>Welcome to John Green's reality. Not too long ago, in New York City, he introduced a screening of the film based on his novel, <em>The Fault in Our Stars</em>, to an audience of hundreds of teenagers ecstatically screaming his name. They cried copiously throughout the film, which follows a romance between two teenagers with cancer.</p>   <p>The next morning, in his hotel suite, Green appeared somewhat dazed. The sandy-haired author said the process of writing a book is like a long, lonely game of Marco Polo.</p>   <div class="container book nobar" id="con318853636" previewTitle="Book Edition Information">
            <div id="res318853712" class="bucketwrap image book" previewTitle="The Fault in Our Stars">
                  <div class="imagewrap">
        <a href="/books/titles/145340771/the-fault-in-our-stars">
                <img src="http://media.npr.org/assets/bakertaylor/covers/t/the-fault-in-our-stars/9780142424179_custom-18ef29c3e3f8fa2344b3029b3272ab512651e213-s99-c85.jpg" data-original="http://media.npr.org/assets/bakertaylor/covers/t/the-fault-in-our-stars/9780142424179_custom-18ef29c3e3f8fa2344b3029b3272ab512651e213-s99.jpg" class="img lazyOnLoad"  title="The Fault in Our Stars" alt="The Fault in Our Stars" />
        </a>
</div>
